Only chips with fat datapaths & off-chip memory (GPU, TPU) need a large batch per chip. If SGD gives best results with batches of N, chips which are efficient for batches of 1 or 2 means you can parallelise training over more chips. So knowing N is important.

This is correct, that is why bigger batches are better near a local minimum. Smaller batches are better in the beginning because they yield more updates. Imagine: If you want to get down a mountain, it is good to initially go down any direction instead of calculating exact slopes
don't forget @graphcoreai @MaxelerTech et al

Variance is not the issue - m small batch updates have the same variance as one large which is the relevant comparison. The fast changing loss surface is the issue but can be solved with LR warmup + momentum (to smooth updates) + careful init as in http:// arxiv.org/abs/1706.02677
Wait what? Doesn't a bigger batch size decrease gradient variance?
Would be great if you could also publish with batch normalization or data augmentation so there is no ambuiguity!
The ResNet20 numbers we publish are without batch normalization or data augmentation so the numbers are lower than someone else’s where they do.

2. For a constant base learning rate (equivalent to adopting the linear scaling rule) increasing batch size increases the variance of the SGD weight updates. The negative effect of this is important early in training, due to rapidly changing dynamics over non-convex loss surface

1. Starting with a smaller batch size and increasing the batch size near convergence generally helps – however, this does not eliminate the fact that a smaller batch size would still allow the use of larger learning rates and produce better test accuracy.
